From a psychological perspective, people often rely on their existing thoughts and views when forming opinions. In some cases, this happens automatically, but in others we consciously consider which arguments are relevant. Framing influences which thoughts are available, considered relevant and easy to recall. The stronger or more relevant a frame appears, the more likely it is to affect our opinions [@chong2007framing].

In this case, the youths will either read *Arbeiderpartiet* (The Labour Party) or *Fremskrittspartiet* (The Progress Party) in a question related to inheritance tax: *…believes that there should be no tax on inheriting large assets. To what extent do you agree or disagree with this statement?*

In this scenario, the respondents might automatically choose their answer based on the party that is mentioned. This emphasizes that we often tend to use thoughts that are available and easy to recall. Sometimes this happens automatically, but at the end of the day, framing influences which thoughts seem most relevant.

